06475nam a22007575i 9780822382027DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19961996ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223820277 a10.1515/97808223820272doi  a(DE-B1597)554147  a(OCoLC)1055051620  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPS169.P35bP37 1996 7aLIT0040202bisacsh00aPassing and the Fictions of Identity /cDonald E. Pease, Elaine K. Ginsberg. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1996] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource (307 p.) :b6 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Americanists00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Politics of Passing -- tI. Passing to Freedom -- tThe Subaltern as Imperialist: Speaking of Olaudah Equiano -- t"A Most Respectable Looking Gentleman": Passing, Possession, and Transgression in Running a Thousand Miles for Freedom -- tII. The (Re)Construction of Race -- tThe Autobiography of an Ex-Coloured Man: (Passing for) Black Passing for White -- tSliding Significations: Passing as a Narrative and Textual Strategy in Nella Larsen's Fiction -- tIII. Blackness and the White Imagination -- tSpanish Masquerade and the Drama of Racial Identity in Uncle Tom's Cabin -- tBlackness and the Literary Imagination: Uncovering The Hidden Hand -- t"A Most Disagreeable Mirror": Reflections on White Identity in Black Like Me -- tIV. Creating the Self -- tConfederate Counterfeit: The Case of the Cross-Dressed Civil War Soldier -- tDisplacing Desire: Passing, Nostalgia, and Giovanni's Room -- tPassing for White, Passing for Black -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPassing refers to the process whereby a person of one race, gender, nationality, or sexual orientation adopts the guise of another. Historically, this has often involved black slaves passing as white in order to gain their freedom. More generally, it has served as a way for women and people of color to access male or white privilege. In their examination of this practice of crossing boundaries, the contributors to this volume offer a unique perspective for studying the construction and meaning of personal and cultural identities.These essays consider a wide range of texts and moments from colonial times to the present that raise significant questions about the political motivations inherent in the origins and maintenance of identity categories and boundaries. Through discussions of such literary works as Running a Thousand Miles for Freedom, The Autobiography of an Ex-Coloured Man, Uncle Tom's Cabin, The Hidden Hand, Black Like Me, and Giovanni's Room, the authors examine issues of power and privilege and ways in which passing might challenge the often rigid structures of identity politics. Their interrogation of the semiotics of behavior, dress, language, and the body itself contributes significantly to an understanding of national, racial, gender, and sexual identity in American literature and culture.Contextualizing and building on the theoretical work of such scholars as Judith Butler, Diana Fuss, Marjorie Garber, and Henry Louis Gates Jr., Passing and the Fictions of Identity will be of value to students and scholars working in the areas of race, gender, and identity theory, as well as U.S. history and literature.Contributors. Martha Cutter, Katharine Nicholson Ings, Samira Kawash, Adrian Piper, Valerie Rohy, Marion Rust, Julia Stern, Gayle Wald, Ellen M. Weinauer, Elizabeth Young  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aAfrican Americans in literature. 0aAfrican AmericansxRace identity. 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aDifference (Psychology) in literature. 0aGender iden